Pavar\u00ebsis\u00eb\u201d Ulqini 2012]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hyka, Klejdi}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Durr\u00ebs]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Albanian footballers]]\n[[Category:KF Teuta Durr\u00ebs players]]\n[[Category:Besa Kavaj\u00eb players]]\n[[Category:KF Korabi Peshkopi players]]\n[[Category:Albanian Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Albanian First Division players]]\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Albanian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Albanian association football player\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klejdi_Hyka"}
{"title_page": "Motivation (Kelly Rowland song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 single by Kelly Rowland}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Motivation\n| cover      = Kelly_Rowland_-_Motivation.jpg\n| alt        = The Blue woman stands to the position hand and with a brown head. The Name of Performer is 'KELLY ROWLAND' and the name of single is 'motivation ft/ lil wayne'\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kelly Rowland]] featuring [[Lil&nbsp;Wayne]]\n| album      = [[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]]\n| released   = {{start date|2011|04|08}}\n| format     = \n*[[music download|Digital download]]\n*[[music streaming|streaming]]\n| recorded   = 2010\n| studio     = \n*Circle House ([[Miami]])\n*[[Sterling Sound]] (New York)\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=51}}\n| label      = [[Universal Motown Records|Universal Motown]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Lil Wayne|Dwayne Carter]]\n*[[Jim Jonsin|James Scheffer]]\n*[[Danny Morris (entertainer)|Danny Morris]]\n*[[Rico Love]]\n| producer   = {{flat list|\n*[[Jim Jonsin]]\n*Rico Love}}\n| chronology = [[Kelly Rowland]]\n| prev_title = [[Gone (Nelly song)|Gone]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[What a Feeling (Alex Gaudino song)|What a Feeling]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Lil Wayne]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[I'm Into You]]\n | prev_year  = 2011\n | title      = Motivation\n | year       = 2011\n | next_title = [[Red Nation]]\n | next_year  = 2011\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Motivation'''\" is a song performed by American recording artist [[Kelly Rowland]], from her third studio album ''[[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]]'' (2011). The song was written by [[Jim Jonsin]], [[Rico Love]], Daniel Morris and [[Lil Wayne]], with Jonsin producing the song and Lil Wayne having featured vocals. The [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] slow-jam serves as the [[lead single]] from ''Here I Am'' and was released from April 8, 2011. Upon release, \"Motivation\" received favorable reviews from critics generally praising the sexiness of the song. Official remixes were produced for the song, including a [[dubstep]]-inspired [[electronic music|electronic]] mix by [[Diplo (producer)|Diplo]] and a rap remix by [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Trey Songz]] and [[Fabolous]].\n\nIn the United States, the song has peaked at number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart where it stayed seven weeks in a row, and number seventeen on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Rowland's second US top 20 hit (fourth top 30 overall) and her second highest performing single to date as a solo artist, behind \"[[Dilemma (song)|Dilemma]]\". It was certified [[double platinum]] by the [[RIAA]] in May 2013.\n\nAn accompanying music video was directed by Sarah Chatfield, the director behind Rowland's previous video \"[[Forever and a Day (Kelly Rowland song)|Forever and a Day]]\" (2010). It follows a number of sultry scenes where Rowland dances seductively amongst partially dressed dancers in a dimly-lit warehouse, with the entire video tinged in blue light. \"Motivation\" was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] at the [[54th Grammy Awards]]. Rowland sang the song with Trey Songz at the [[BET Awards of 2011|2011 BET Awards]] ceremony.\n\n==Background and release==\n''Here I Am'' was originally scheduled for release in 2010, but was pushed back numerous times. Initially the [[dance music|dance]]-influenced \"[[Commander (song)|Commander]]\" served as the album's [[lead single]] for international territories while two separate singles were serviced in the United States. \"[[Rose Colored Glasses (Kelly Rowland song)|Rose Colored Glasses]]\" for the [[Contemporary hit radio|pop]] format and \"[[Grown Woman (Kelly Rowland song)|Grown Woman]]\" for the [[urban contemporary|urban]] format.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/press/ldquocommanderrdquo-featuring-david-guetta,1372294.html |title=Kelly Rowland Scores No. 1 Hit on Billboard\u2019s Dance/Club Play Songs Chart with \"Commander,\" Featuring David Guetta |publisher=The Earth Times |author=Universal Motown Records Group |date=2010-07-06 |accessdate=2010-07-07 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5srof0lkH |archivedate=2011-09-19}}</ref><ref name=\"Single Plans\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a225421/kelly-rowland-alters-single-release-plans.html |title=Kelly Rowland Alters Single Release Plans |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. ([[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]]) |last=Copsey |first=Robert |date=2010-06-11 |accessdate=2010-06-26}}</ref> Rowland decided in September 2010 to re-enter the recording studios to work on new material for the album.<ref name=\"Catarinella 2010-09\">{{cite web |url=http://www.papermag.com/2010/09/news_flash_moschino_knows_how.php |title=Kelly Rowland on Destiny's Child Fashion Mishaps and Loving the Gays |publisher=(Paper Publishing Company) |work=[[Paper (magazine)|PAPER]] |last=Catarinella |first=Alex |date=2010-09-11 |accessdate=2010-09-12}}</ref> This, coupled with creative issues such as naming the album, led to multiple pushbacks. \"Motivation\" was announced as the title for the album's new lead single during [[New York Fashion Week]].<ref name=\"New Single Announcement\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kellyrowland.com/kelly-daily/128-kelly-announces-qmotivationq-as-the-official-lead-single-on-upcoming-album.html |title=Kelly Announces 'Motivation' as the Official Lead Single on Upcoming Album |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xevherxX?url=http://www.kellyrowland.com/kelly-daily/128-kelly-announces-qmotivationq-as-the-official-lead-single-on-upcoming-album.html |archivedate=2011-04-03 |publisher=Kellyrowland.com ([[Universal Motown]] / [[Kelly Rowland]]) |date=2011-02-27 |accessdate=2011-04-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It debuted online via ''[[Rap-Up]]'' magazine's website on March 2, 2011.<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/03/02/new-music-kelly-rowland-f-lil-wayne-motivation/ |title=New Music: Kelly Rowland feat. Lil Wayne \u2013 Motivation |publisher=Rap-Up.com ([[Rap-Up]]) |date=2011-03-02 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking of how the record came about, Rowland said \"Motivation came about when I was in the studio with [producers] Jim Jonsin and Rico Love, and we kind of were just vibing. I told Rico I wanted something really sexy ... and he came up with 'Motivation' along with Jim. It turned into this amazing record... I played [&nbsp;'Motivation' for [[Lil Wayne]]&nbsp;] and he got on it, and it was just as simple as that.\"<ref name=\"Vena\"/> Along with the single announcement, ''Rap-Up'' said fans could expect the video and a remix produced by [[Diplo (DJ)|Diplo]] to premiere in April 2011.<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\"/> However, the [[electronic music|electronic]] remix, produced by Diplo, premiered via ''Rap-Up'' on March 8, 2011.<ref name=\"Diplo Remix\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/03/08/new-music-kelly-rowland-f-lil-wayne-motivation-diplo-remix/#more-76993 |title=New Music: Kelly Rowland f/ Lil Wayne \u2013 \u2018Motivation (Diplo Remix)\u2019 |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date= |accessdate=2011-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen |filename = KellyRowland Motivation.ogg |title = \"Motivation\" (2011) |description = A 23-second sample of \"Motivation\", backed by slow R&B beats. The lyrics of the song, described as \"racy\" sees Rowland asking her partner to move his hands over her body. |format =[[Ogg]] |pos = right}}\n\"Motivation\" is a [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] slow jam song written by [[Rico Love|Richard Butler (Rico Love)]], [[Jim Jonsin]], [[Lil Wayne|Dwayne Carter]] and [[Danny Morris (entertainer)|Danny Morris]].<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\"/><ref name=\"Bain\"/> The racy lyrics center around Rowland asking her man to use his hands all over her body, and are accompanied by a \"[[synthesizer|synth]]-saturated beat\" produced by Jonsin.<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\"/> In terms of instruments, \"Motivation\" uses sparse [[keyboard (music)|keyboard]] notes, programmed beats and pulsing synths in the [[refrain|chorus]].<ref name=\"Shetler\"/> Wayne adds a rap verse complementing Rowland's seductive suggestions, using the kitchen and a car as metaphors for sex.<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\"/><ref name=\"Shetler\"/> According to Scott Shetler from AOL Music, Rowland uses the lyrics to promise \"to be her lover's motivation.\"<ref name=\"Shetler\"/> Rowland called the record a mixture between [[dance music|dance]] and [[Mashup (music)|mash-up]].<ref name=\"New Single Announcement\"/> When asked by [[MTV]] what Rowland thought of the song, she said,\"It has that personality and characteristic to it that I don't think anybody can deny. That's why when Wayne dropped that insane verse on there ... I was like, 'You really brought that up even more.' He went into the studio and just did it. I don't think it takes much for Wayne to think. He just does it. He's so admirable.\"<ref name=\"Vena\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1661290/kelly-rowland-lil-wayne-motivation-video.jhtml |title=Kelly Rowland Feels 'Uber-Duber Sexy' On Lil Wayne Collabo 'Motivation' |publisher=[[MTV News]]. ([[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]: [[MTV Networks]]) |date=2011-04-04 |last=Vena |first=Jocelyn |accessdate=2011-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[File:Lil Wayne in Concert.jpg|thumb|150px|left|[[Lil Wayne]] (pictured) is featured on the single, and his verses received positive reviews.]]\nRyan Brockington, from the ''[[New York Post]],'' was amongst the first to review \"Motivation.\" In his review, he said \"The single is a big leap from the dance club synth pop that Kelly has been releasing the past year and it seems like she might be trying to shimmy her way back into the [[hip hop music|hip-hop]] world by teaming up with the Midas touch vocals of [[Lil Wayne]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/will_this_track_get_kelly_rowland_d6LUq73KeegKPXsFJ6YaHL |title=Will 'Motivation' get Kelly Rowland back on 'top?' |work=[[New York Post]] |publisher=(NYP Holdings Ltd.) |last=Brockington |first=Ryan |date=2011-03-03 |accessdate=2011-04-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304181300/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/will_this_track_get_kelly_rowland_d6LUq73KeegKPXsFJ6YaHL |archive-date=2011-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both ''[[Rap-Up]]'' and [[AOL]] Music's Scott Shetler called the song \"sexy.\"<ref name=\"Rap-Up Debut\"/><ref name=\"Shetler\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aolradioblog.com/2011/03/17/kelly-rowland-motivation-lil-wayne/ |title=Kelly Rowland, 'Motivation' Feat. Lil Wayne \u2013 New Song |publisher=AOL Music. ([[AOL]]) |last=Shetler |first=Scott |date=2011-03-17 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref> Becky Bain from Idolator disliked the song for not being memorable. The short review was summed up with the closing phrase, \"she's going to need another hit to help promote her album when it finally is ready to drop.\"<ref name=\"Bain\">{{cite web |url=http://idolator.com/5785762/kelly-rowland-lil-wayne-motivation |title=Kelly Rowland And Lil Wayne Seek Some \"Motivation\" On New Track |publisher=Idolator.com (Buzzmedia) |last=Bain |first=Becky |date=2011-03-11 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref> Wesley Case from ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' complimented the song's sexy quality. \"If this isn't the year's hands-down sexiest song thus far, it has to be in the discussion. Rowland, whose sultry voice could get a priest hot, weaving in and out of the minimal beat, and setting the table for Lil Wayne's stuttering, after-hours guest-verse. Stack the pieces together and it's an understated knockout that gets sexier with each spin.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/bthesite/louder-now-blog/bal-kelly-rowland-recuits-lil-wayne-for-motivation-video-20110405,0,4525167.story |title=Kelly Rowland's 'Motivation': Sexiest song of the year? |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |publisher=([[Tribune Company]]) |date=2011-04-05 |accessdate=2011-04-05 |last=Case |first=Wesley}}</ref> Shahryar Rizvi of ''[[Dallas Observer]]'' felt that the song was a \"female-fronted counterpart\" to the smooth, slow-[[tempo]] [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] vibe that [[R. Kelly]] and [[Trey Songz]] usually proffer.<ref>{{cite  web|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/music/in-defense-of-kelly-rowlands-motivation-feat-lil-wayne-7046672|title=In Defense of... Kelly Rowland's \"Motivation (feat. Lil Wayne)\"|last=Rizvi|first=Shahryar|date=2011-08-09|website=Dallas Observer|url-status=live}}</ref> Billboard ranked it number five on their \"Critics' Picks: 20 Best Songs of 2011\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/464742/critics-picks-20-best-songs-of-2011 |title=Critics' Picks: 20 Best Songs of 2011 |url-status=live |accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Motivation\" was nominated for two awards at the [[2011 Soul Train Music Awards]] including Best Dance Performance and Song of the Year. It won the award for Song of the Year and was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] at the [[54th Grammy Awards]], which was held on February 12, 2012.\n\nIn 2019, ''[[The Associated Press]]'' named the song number 2 out of 25 songs listed as a part of its \"Top songs of the decade\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/f31fc68f64ff87b615173bae95441fd9 |title=AP\u2019s top songs of the decade: Robyn, Kelly Rowland, Drake |accessdate=14 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nDespite not being released for [[music download|digital download]] until April 13, 2011, \"Motivation\" made its US chart debuted on April 2, debuting at number fifty-five on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart.<ref name=\"US Download\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2011-04-02/r-b-hip-hop-songs?order=gainer |title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Songs Gainers |publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]]) |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=2011-03-28 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref> In the weeks following it continued to rise thanks to urban airplay, eventually reaching number one in its tenth week on the chart, chart dated May 23, 2011.<ref name=\"sc_Billboardrandbhiphop_Kelly Rowland\"/> \"Motivation\" is Rowland's first solo number one as lead artist on a US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' composite chart (one combining airplay and sales), although she previously peaked at number one with [[Nelly]] on his 2002 single \"[[Dilemma (song)|Dilemma]].\"<ref name=\"Ramirez\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/470968/chart-juice-kelly-rowland-hits-no-1-on-rbhip-hop-songs |title=Chart Juice: Kelly Rowland Hits No. 1 on R&B/Hip-Hop Songs |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |last=Ramirez |first=Erika |date=2011-05-27 |accessdate=2011-05-28}}</ref> It stayed at the top spot of the chart for six more weeks. In the same week that \"Motivation\" hit number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart, [[Lil Wayne]], who is featured on the single, had a total of twelve songs on the chart.<ref name=\"Ramirez\"/>\n\nFollowing its release, \"Motivation\" debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number fifty-five, Rowland's highest Hot 100 debut as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Grein\">{{cite web|url=http://new.music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart_watch/74355/week-ending-april-17-2011-songs-youth-will-be-served/|title=Week Ending April 17, 2011. Songs: Youth Will Be Served|date=April 20, 2011|first=Paul|last=Grein|publisher=Chart Watch ([[Yahoo! Music]])|accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> It reached number seventeen, Rowland's highest Hot 100 peak as a solo artist, and best chart position since \"Dilemma\" (by [[Nelly]] featuring Kelly Rowland \u22122002), which reached number one.<ref name=\"Ramirez\"/> Additionally, it is the first single from Rowland to chart on the Hot 100 since her 2009 feature on [[David Guetta]]'s \"[[When Love Takes Over]]\", which reached number seventy-six.<ref name=\"Ramirez\"/> The previous two lead singles, \"[[Grown Woman (Kelly Rowland song)|Grown Woman]]\" (2010) and \"[[Rose Colored Glasses (Kelly Rowland song)|Rose Colored Glasses]]\" (2010), from ''[[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]],'' failed to enter the Hot 100, though the latter peaked at number fifty-one on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart. The producer of \"Motivation\", [[Jim Jonsin]], said he was proud and confident of the song's success. \"I'm really happy that things are going well for her on this record. A real concern for us was to get that smash for her... She's a friend of ours as well, so to see her win is huge.\"<ref name=\"rap-up1\"/>\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:Kelly Rowland - Motivation (Screenshot - 1)(LQ).jpg|thumb|200px|right|One of the blue light-shaded scenes from the video, where Kelly Rowland sings seductively, while other people get romantic in the background.]]\n\nThe [[music video]] for \"Motivation\" was directed by [[Sarah Chatfield]], at the end of March 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videostatic.com/vs/2011/03/shot-kelly-rowland-f-lil-wayne-sarah-chatfield-dir.html |title=SHOT: Kelly Rowland f/ Lil Wayne \u2013 Sarah Chatfield, dir. |publisher=Vidostatic.com |last=Gottlieb |first=Steven |date=2011-03-24 |accessdate=2011-04-03}}</ref> Frank Gatson served as the video's chroegrapher.<ref name=\"Vena\"/> Speaking during Roberto Cavalli's fashion show, Rowland said she was on the look out for \"womanly, sexy designs\" for a \"feminine sexy video.\"<ref name=\"New Single Announcement\"/> She elaborated on the development of the video during an interview when [[MTV News]]' Jocelyn Vena. She told Vena, \"We came up with the energy, and with Frank [Gatson] \u2014 and I don't know how he sees something, but he got it... I'm so thankful I have a great team that's thinking 10 steps ahead of me. With Sarah she understood; she got the concept. It was great the way everything came together.\"<ref name=\"Vena\"/> The video made its world premiere on [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]]'s ''[[106 & Park]]'' on April 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2011/04/04/kelly-rowland-premieres-steamy-new-video-for-motivation-.html |title=Kelly Rowland Premieres Steamy New Video For \"Motivation\" |publisher=Bet.com ([[Black Entertainment Television]]) |last=Charlton |first=Lauretta |date=2011-04-04 |accessdate=2011-04-05}}</ref>\n\nThe video opens in a blue-colored hue lit warehouse, with Rowland standing in the passageway before it cuts to her walking through the building checking out the ladies and men mingling. Rowland can then be seen in a purple swimsuit & coat, doing different sexual choreography routines with her many half-dressed male backup dancers. The clip then shows Lil Wayne in his own scene rapping his verse to the song. He can then be seen leaning against a wall and standing on a bed with the lights flashing while Rowland is simultaneously being entertained by a male dancer as she sits upon a chair. The video then continues with the crowd entwining with each other; full make out sections between females and their male counterparts, as well as half-dressed males feeling on each other's bodies, while the females also interact with each other. After more dancing from Rowland and her dancers, the video then ends with Rowland singing her last lines, surrounded by the sexually charged crowd. Jocelyn Vena of MTV commented that the video \"plays to the song's sexy themes.\"<ref name=\"Vena\"/>\n\n==Remixes==\n[[File:Diplo 2014 Press Photo (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|left|[[Electronic dance music|EDM]] DJ/producer [[Diplo]] produced the song's official remix.]]\n\"Motivation\" has been remixed several times, mainly by Rowland's fellow R&B contemporaries who have each put their own angle on the song. The first remix, the song's official remix, was helmed by Alternative [[electronic music]] producer, [[Diplo (producer)|Diplo]]. It replaces some of the song's original instruments with electronic ones, as well as adding \"rapid [[Hi-hat (instrument)|hi-hats]]\"<ref name=\"Diplo Remix\"/> Diplo also modifies Rowland's vocals, by \"chopping and reconfiguring\" them \"over the [[dubstep]]-inspired instrumental.\"<ref name=\"Diplo Remix\"/> A [[So So Def]] remix of the song features female American rapper [[Da Brat]]. The unofficial remix, features a new introduction from Da Brat, and was released online to ''[[Rap-Up]]''.<ref name=\"rap-up1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/05/10/new-music-da-brat-f-kelly-rowland-motivation-so-so-def-remix/ |title=New Music: Da Brat f/ Kelly Rowland \u2013 \u2018Motivation (So So Def Remix)\u2019 |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date= |accessdate=2011-05-20}}</ref> R&B singers [[The-Dream]] and [[Jeremih]] also made remixes of the song, adding their own verses and \"male perspective\" to complement Rowland and [[Lil Wayne]]'s verses.[[Tyga]] also released a remix for his Mixtape \"Well Done 2\" entitled \"Pussy Talkin'.<ref>{{cite web |author=Ed Easton Jr. |url=http://923now.radio.com/2011/05/17/jeremih-joins-kelly-rowland-lil-wayne-on-motivation-remix/ |title=Jeremih Joins Kelly Rowland & Lil Wayne On \"Motivation\" Remix |publisher=923now.radio.com |date=2011-05-16 |accessdate=2011-05-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520211935/http://923now.radio.com/2011/05/17/jeremih-joins-kelly-rowland-lil-wayne-on-motivation-remix/ |archive-date=2011-05-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In May 2011, [[R. Kelly]] joined the list of singers to create their own remix for \"Motivation\". In his version, R. Kelly adds additional verses and references his own songs such as \"Pregnant\".<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/5880772/kelly-rowland-motivation-remix-r-kelly |title=Kelly Rowland\u2019s \"Motivation\" Remix War: R. Kelly Vs. The-Dream Vs. Jeremih Vs Diplo &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date=2011-05-27 |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> R. Kelly's remix of the song was praised by Rowland. Using her official [[Twitter]] account, Rowland said, \"R. Kelly Motivation Remix is CRAAAZZZZZY!!!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Rankin |first=Kenrya |url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2011/06/01/kelly-rowland-s-motivation-1-stars-remix-track.html |title=Kelly Rowland's \"Motivation\" #1, Stars Remix Track &#124; News |publisher=BET |date= |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> R&B singer [[Mario (entertainer)|Mario]] also added his vocals to a remix of the song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/Content/EntertainmentNews.aspx?Section=2&Id=1641277&SM=1 |title=Kelly Rowland Releases Official Motivation Remix |publisher=Rttnews.com |date=2011-06-08 |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> On June 6, 2011, a second official remix for the song was uploaded. It replaces [[Lil Wayne]] with new verses from rappers [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Trey Songz]] and [[Fabolous]].<ref name=\"Second Remix\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prefixmag.com/media/kelly-rowland/motivation-f-busta-rhymes-fabolous-trey-songz-remi/52973/ |title=Kelly Rowland: \"Motivation\" F. Busta Rhymes, Fabolous & Trey Songz (Remix) |publisher=Prefixmag.com |date=2011-06-06 |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> Rhymes has a rapid-fire \"bedroom\"-themed verse, while Songz sings in his [[falsetto]] and Fabolous' verse is cut short by the re-introduction of Rowland's vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/06/06/new-music-kelly-rowland-f-busta-rhymes-trey-songz-fabolous-motivation-remix/ |title=New Music: Kelly Rowland f/ Busta Rhymes, Trey Songz, & Fabolous \u2013 \u2018Motivation (Remix)\u2019 |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> A third officially produced remix, the \"Rebel Rock Remix,\" features on the deluxe edition of ''[[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]]''.<ref name=\"Here I Am\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\n[[File:Trey Songz SummerJam.jpg|thumb|150px|right|[[Trey Songz]] who appeared alongside Rowland to perform \"Motivation\" at the [[BET Awards of 2011|2011 BET Awards]].]]\nOn June 26, 2011, Rowland took to the stage of the [[BET Awards of 2011|2011 BET Awards]] to perform \"Motivation\" for the first time in public. The performance was part of the evening's entertainment; the song was not nominated for an award. Hollywood News reported that Rowland was among the most anticipated performers of the evening.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodnews.com/2011/06/26/kelly-rowland-among-most-anticipated-performers-at-bet-awards/ |title=Kelly Rowland among most anticipated performers at BET Awards |publisher=Hollywoodnews.com |last=Palacios |first=Kim |date=2011-06-26 |accessdate=2011-07-03}}</ref> Appearing in the middle of [[Trey Songz]] performance of \"[[Love Faces]],\" Rowland ascended on stage where she was joined by several shirtless male dancers.<ref name=\"Masley\">{{cite web |url=http://www.azcentral.com/thingstodo/music/articles/2011/06/26/20110626bet-awards-chris-brown-kelly-rowland-jill-scott-beyonce.html |title=BET Awards highlights: Kelly Rowland, Jill Scott, Beyonc\u00e9 |work=[[The Arizona Republic]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]] |last=Masley |first=Ed |date=2011-06-26 |accessdate=2011-07-03}}</ref> The performance was met with a positive reception from industry critics and fellow music entertainers, most of whom noted it as a highlight of the ceremony. Ed Masley from ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' said that Rowland's performance was \"the night's most soulful vocal [performance].\"<ref name=\"Masley\"/> Roger Catlin said that Rowland offered \"a live performance with Trey Songz trumping that of her more famous 'sister' from [[Destiny's Child]], [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles|Beyonc\u00e9]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.courant.com/roger_catlin_tv_eye/2011/06/sibliing-rivalries-and-a-slip.html |title=Sibliing Rivalries and a Slip at the BET Awards |publisher=Courant.com |last=Catlin |first=Roger |date=2011-06-27 |accessdate=2011-07-03 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707225203/http://blogs.courant.com/roger_catlin_tv_eye/2011/06/sibliing-rivalries-and-a-slip.html |archive-date=2012-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Gerrick D. Kennedy praised Rowland's sex appeal, noting that her \"steamy performance sent tongues wagging\" and was widely anticipated thanks to the serial delays with her album ''[[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]]'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/awards/2011/06/bet-awards-2011-crowns-chris-brown-the-comeback-kid.html |title=BET Awards 2011 crown Chris Brown the comeback kid |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |last=Kennedy |first=Gerrick D. |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2011-07-04}}</ref> [[MTV]] Rob Markman pointed out that following her performance, the hashtag \"#kelly\" began [[Trending topic|trending]] on [[Twitter]]. Additionally Markman said Rowland \"received one of the loudest ovations of the night.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1666441/bet-awards.jhtml |title=Chris Brown Wins Big, Lil Wayne, Beyonce Rock 2011 BET Awards |publisher=MTV. ([[MTV Networks]]) |last=Markman |first=Rob |date=2011-06-27 |accessdate=2011-07-04}}</ref> \n\nRowland performed the song on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]] on September 27, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://defpen.com/video-kelly-rowland-motivation-x-lay-it-on-me-jimmy-kimmel-live/ |title=Video: Kelly Rowland \u2013 Motivation x Lay It On Me (Jimmy Kimmel Live) |website=[[Def Pen]] |date=2011-09-28}}</ref> ''[[Rap-Up]]'' described Rowland's performance on the show as a \"sizzling performance\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Kelly Rowland Performs With Big Sean on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!' [Video] |url=https://www.rap-up.com/2011/09/27/kelly-rowland-performs-with-big-sean-on-jimmy-kimmel-live-video/ |publisher=Rap-Up.com |accessdate=2011-09-27}}</ref> Robbie Daw of ''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' praised Rowland's performance and said that the \"black-clad diva rocked out two sexy jams from Here I Am\" and later described her performance as \"sultry\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daw |first1=Robbie |title=Kelly Rowland Finds Her Motivation On \u2018Jimmy Kimmel Live\u2019 |url=https://www.idolator.com/6026402/kelly-rowland-jimmy-kimmel-live?chrome=1 |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |publisher=Idolator.com |date=2011-09-27}}</ref> Rowland performed the song during her guest appearance on ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'' on June 24, 2013 along with \"[[Kisses Down Low]]\" and \"[[Street Life (Kelly Rowland song)|Street Life]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Must See: Kelly Rowland Performs \u2018Kisses Down Low\u2019 & \u2018Motivation\u2019 Live At \u2018The Wendy Williams Show\u2019 |url=https://thatgrapejuice.net/2013/06/kelly-rowland-performs-kisses-low-motivation-live-the-wendy-williams-show/ |publisher=ThatGrapeJuice.net |date=June 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Joszor |first1=Njai |title=Kelly Rowland Talks Wigs, New Relationship and Performs on \u2018Wendy Williams\u2019 |url=https://singersroom.com/content/2013-06-25/kelly-rowland-talks-wigs-new-relationship-and-performs-on-wendy-williams/ |work=[[Singersroom]] |publisher=Singersroom.com |date=June 25, 2013 |accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''Digital download'''<ref name=\"US Download\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B004UPD41S/|title=Motivation: Kelly Rowland: MP3 Downloads |publisher=Amazon.com |date=2011-04-12|accessdate=2011-04-08}}</ref>\n#\"Motivation\" featuring [[Lil Wayne]] \u2013 3:51\n\n*'''Digital download Remix'''<ref name=\"US Diplo\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/motivation-diplo-remix-single/id429799995|title=Motivation (Diplo Remix) \u2013 Single |publisher=iTunes |date=2011-04-12 |accessdate=2011-04-14}}</ref>\n#\"Motivation\" ([[Diplo (producer)|Diplo]] Remix) \u2013 3:56\n\n*'''Rap remix (streaming)'''<ref name=\"Second Remix\"/>\n#\"Motivation\" featuring [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Fabolous]] and [[Trey Songz]] \u2013 4:34\n{{col-2}}\n*'''Rebel Rock Remix (album-only)'''<ref name=\"Here I Am\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/13981817 |title=Kelly Rowland reveals Here I Am album track list |publisher=[[BBC News]]beat. ([[British Broadcasting Corporation]]) |date=2011-07-01 |accessdate=2011-07-02}}</ref>\n:13. \"Motivation\" featuring Lil Wayne (Rebel Rock Remix) \u2013 3:41\n\n*'''Digital single/bundle'''<ref name=\"DS/B\"/>\n#\"Motivation\" featuring Lil Wayne \u2013 3:51\n#\"Motivation\" (Diplo remix) \u2013 3:57\n#\"Motivation\" (Explicit Version; [[Closed captioned]]) <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Music video]] \u2013 4:22\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n'''Recording'''<ref name=\"album credits\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Here I Am (Kelly Rowland album)|Here I Am]] |others=[[Kelly Rowland]] |date=2011 |type=liner notes |publisher=[[Universal Motown Records]]}}</ref>\n*Recorded and mixed at Circle House Recording Studios in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]\n*Mastered at Sterling Sound in [[New York City, New York]]\n\n'''Personnel'''<ref name=\"album credits\"/>\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Jim Jonsin]] \u2013 songwriter, producer, programming, keyboards\n*[[Rico Love]] \u2013 songwriter\n*Daniel Morris \u2013 songwriter, keyboards\n*[[Lil Wayne|Dwayne Carter]] \u2013 songwriter, featured rap vocals\n*Thurston McCrea \u2013 recording\n*Sean McCoy \u2013 recording assistant, mixing assistant\n*Robert Marks \u2013 additional recording, mixing\n*Matt Huber \u2013 mixing assistant\n*Chris Gehringer \u2013 mastering\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Awards ceremony\n!Award\n!Results\n!Ref\n|-\n| 2011\n| MP3 Music Awards\n| Music Industry Choice Award\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Wretch 32 and Adele win at the 2011 MP3 Music Awards|url= http://www.nme.com/news/wretch-32/60921|magazine=[[NME]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2011\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Soul Train Music Awards]]\n|Best Dance Performance\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1672938/soul-train-awards-nominations/|title=Chris Brown, Beyonce Lead Soul Train Award Nods|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|website=MTV News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref><ref name=\"soultrain\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2011/11/2011-soul-train-awards-performances-and-winners|title=The 2011 Soul Train Awards Performances and Winners|date=2011-11-28|website=Vibe|language=en|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|Song of the Year\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"soultrain\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2012\n|[[Billboard Music Awards]]\n|Top R&B Song\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/entertainment/2012/05/adele_lmfao_and_coldplay_domin.html|title=Adele, LMFAO and Coldplay dominate 2012 Billboard Music Awards|last=Staff|first=Masslive Com|date=2012-05-21|website=masslive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Grammy Awards]]\n|Best Rap/Sung Collaboration\n|{{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/16002822/kelly-rowland-discusses-beyonce-award-rivalry|title=Kelly Rowland discusses Beyonce award rivalry|last=McIntosh|first=Steven|date=2011-02-12|website=BBC Newsbeat|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\n|-\n|}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011\u201312) !! Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia Urban ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_urban.asp?chart=1Q40RB&chart2=1R40RB |title=Top 40 Urban Albums & Singles Chart \u2013 2/5/2011 |publisher